# Rule: stack-lock

This project uses a fixed, minimal technology stack. No agent may deviate without explicit user instruction.

## Allowed

| Concern | Choice |
|---|---|
| Markup | HTML5 (single index.html file) |
| Styling | Plain CSS using CSS variables (in tokens.css and main.css) |
| Utility classes | Tailwind CDN (loaded via script tag in HTML head) |
| Logic | Vanilla JavaScript (ES2020 features OK) |
| State | Plain JS object on window, with localStorage for persistence |
| Data | Plain JS objects in scripts/cases.js |

## Prohibited

- React, Vue, Angular, Svelte, or any framework
- TypeScript or JSX
- npm, yarn, pnpm, package.json, node_modules
- Vite, webpack, esbuild, or any build tool
- Sass, Less, PostCSS, CSS Modules
- Any state management library (Redux, Zustand, etc.)
- Backend calls, fetch to APIs, GraphQL
- Server-side rendering
- Service workers (for v1)

## What to Do When Asked to Use a Prohibited Technology

Reply with:
> "This project uses vanilla HTML/CSS/JS only — no [requested tech]. I can implement [feature] using [vanilla equivalent] instead. Should I proceed?"

Wait for confirmation before proceeding.

## File Discipline

- All HTML in one file: `index.html`
- All custom CSS split across `styles/tokens.css` (variables only) and `styles/main.css` (component styles)
- All JS split across `scripts/state.js`, `scripts/cases.js`, `scripts/scoring.js`, `scripts/router.js`, `scripts/main.js`
- Never create new top-level folders or files outside this structure without asking

## Browser Targets

Chrome 109+ and Firefox ESR 115+. No IE polyfills. No Safari-only features.
